1
00:00:47,255 --> 00:00:48,673
[breathing heavily]

2
00:01:00,435 --> 00:01:01,436
[grunting] [groans]

3
00:01:28,004 --> 00:01:32,759
[muffled sound of car door opening
and footsteps approaching]

4
00:01:45,105 --> 00:01:45,939
[man exclaims]

5
00:01:48,316 --> 00:01:51,277
[Matt softly] Father Lantom.
Clinton Church.

6
00:01:56,199 --> 00:01:58,910
-[low rumbling sound]
-[water trickling faintly]

7
00:02:04,833 --> 00:02:06,376
[Maggie] ...bright idea to bring him in?

8
00:02:06,459 --> 00:02:09,420
[Lantom] He's one of ours, Maggie.
What other choice did I have?

9
00:02:09,504 --> 00:02:12,298
[Maggie] Metro-General maybe? Call 911.

10
00:02:12,382 --> 00:02:13,591
[Lantom] He's a vigilante.

11
00:02:13,675 --> 00:02:16,219
If he goes to a hospital,
the police will arrest him.

12
00:02:18,304 --> 00:02:20,682
[Maggie] This is Sister Maggie Grace
at St. Agnes Orphanage--

13
00:02:20,765 --> 00:02:22,976
[Lantom] It's Matthew. Jack Murdock's son.

14
00:02:25,061 --> 00:02:27,063
[Maggie] I'm very sorry. I made a mistake.

15
00:02:29,858 --> 00:02:32,402
Get wire cutters.
We need to get him out of this suit.

16
00:02:32,485 --> 00:02:35,280
Go to the kitchen and bring... we have.

17
00:02:35,363 --> 00:02:37,115
-[Lantom] How can I help?
-You've done enough.

18
00:02:44,372 --> 00:02:45,874
[Matt] <i>Where did you go, Elektra?</i>

19
00:02:49,919 --> 00:02:51,921
<i>-We're gonna die here.</i>
<i>-</i>[Elektra pants]

20
00:02:52,005 --> 00:02:54,757
[Elektra] <i>This is what living feels like.</i>

21
00:03:14,319 --> 00:03:16,362
[nun 1] Get Maggie. Tell her he's awake.

22
00:03:16,446 --> 00:03:17,530
[Matt] Elektra...

23
00:03:17,614 --> 00:03:20,575
-[nun 1] How do you feel?
-[Maggie] Don't try to stand up.

24
00:03:20,658 --> 00:03:21,743
Where... where...

25
00:03:21,826 --> 00:03:23,912
St. Agnes. The orphanage.

26
00:03:23,995 --> 00:03:26,831
-How long? How long?
-Lay down. Several weeks.

27
00:03:28,666 --> 00:03:30,335
-Where is she?
-Who?

28
00:03:30,418 --> 00:03:31,377
Elektra. I...

29
00:03:31,461 --> 00:03:32,712
-I don't know who that is.
-[groans]

30
00:03:32,795 --> 00:03:34,214
Stay in the bed.

31
00:03:34,297 --> 00:03:36,591
-You'll hurt yourself.
-My right ear... I can't...

32
00:03:36,674 --> 00:03:39,135
-Just stop this right now!
-[groans]

33
00:03:44,015 --> 00:03:45,600
-[groans]
-Damn it, Matthew!

34
00:03:45,683 --> 00:03:48,478
Now I can't see. I can't see.

35
00:03:49,145 --> 00:03:50,605
[young Matt] <i>I can't see!</i>

36
00:03:50,688 --> 00:03:53,066
<i>I can't see! I can't see!</i>

37
00:03:53,149 --> 00:03:55,151
[theme music playing]

38
00:04:57,839 --> 00:04:59,674
[Matt breathing heavily]

39
00:05:13,479 --> 00:05:14,689
[Lantom] Matthew?

40
00:05:17,358 --> 00:05:18,401
Father.

41
00:05:20,361 --> 00:05:21,779
I didn't know you were there.

42
00:05:25,491 --> 00:05:27,702
Must feel strange to be back here.

43
00:05:28,661 --> 00:05:30,038
The place where you grew up.

44
00:05:30,997 --> 00:05:32,749
I haven't thanked you yet, Father.

45
00:05:32,832 --> 00:05:36,127
Figured we could count on the nuns
for their discretion.

46
00:05:37,086 --> 00:05:41,132
The nuns know who you are,
but Sister Maggie swore them to secrecy.

47
00:05:41,215 --> 00:05:42,842
After she swore at me.

48
00:05:44,886 --> 00:05:48,181
If you want to take Communion...

49
00:05:48,890 --> 00:05:50,266
we could, uh...

50
00:05:51,434 --> 00:05:53,019
Or we could just talk.

51
00:05:59,233 --> 00:06:00,610
[stammers] Elektra...

52
00:06:02,153 --> 00:06:04,822
was with me when the building collapsed.

53
00:06:04,906 --> 00:06:08,076
Matthew, Elektra passed months ago.

54
00:06:08,701 --> 00:06:11,204
-We had a funeral for her.
-No, shh... I remember.

55
00:06:12,121 --> 00:06:15,333
I know it sounds crazy.
I'm telling you, she was there.

56
00:06:16,250 --> 00:06:17,335
I was...

57
00:06:17,418 --> 00:06:19,879
holding on to her when...

58
00:06:20,588 --> 00:06:24,342
In any case, the building was surrounded
when it collapsed.

59
00:06:25,176 --> 00:06:27,387
Nobody else was seen getting out.

60
00:06:28,221 --> 00:06:30,014
I am so sorry, Matthew.

61
00:06:32,392 --> 00:06:35,770
How about I take your confession
and we go ahead with the Eucharist?

62
00:06:38,231 --> 00:06:39,649
Not today, Father.

63
00:06:40,066 --> 00:06:41,275
[Lantom chuckles softly]

64
00:06:42,068 --> 00:06:44,737
Mystical thinking is not my bag, Matthew.

65
00:06:44,821 --> 00:06:49,242
Hell, I'm probably the most rational crank
in the whole diocese,

66
00:06:49,325 --> 00:06:54,205
but even I have to admit...
it is a miracle you survived.

67
00:06:58,709 --> 00:07:01,504
Our conversations,
they usually go this way.

68
00:07:03,589 --> 00:07:08,761
I come to you with questions.
You tell me what you understand about God.

69
00:07:08,845 --> 00:07:11,848
-Nature of the gig, I guess.
-Give it a rest, shall we?

70
00:07:12,890 --> 00:07:13,891
Sure.

71
00:07:16,310 --> 00:07:18,104
I'll be around. I'll, uh...

72
00:07:20,690 --> 00:07:22,525
When you're ready to talk...

73
00:07:25,194 --> 00:07:26,612
we'll talk.

74
00:07:30,867 --> 00:07:32,326
[door creaking]

75
00:07:32,410 --> 00:07:33,578
[orphan] Is he dead?

76
00:07:37,498 --> 00:07:38,458
Boo.

77
00:07:39,542 --> 00:07:42,170
-[whispering] Who are you?
-Same as you.

78
00:07:43,171 --> 00:07:44,297
I grew up here.

79
00:07:44,380 --> 00:07:46,466
Damn! What happened to you?

80
00:07:47,884 --> 00:07:49,135
Life.

81
00:07:49,218 --> 00:07:51,053
This room is off limits.

82
00:07:52,305 --> 00:07:56,392
And if you're well enough to be up,
you're well enough to be in class.

83
00:07:56,476 --> 00:07:57,643
[both] Sorry, Sister.

84
00:08:01,939 --> 00:08:02,773
Hello again, Matthew.

85
00:08:04,192 --> 00:08:05,818
They're scared of you, huh?

86
00:08:06,694 --> 00:08:08,821
So were you when you were their age.

87
00:08:12,366 --> 00:08:14,076
I need to change your gauze.

88
00:08:14,869 --> 00:08:17,371
Preferably without you flailing around
like an idiot.

89
00:08:21,375 --> 00:08:24,128
I guess I shouldn't be surprised
by any of this.

90
00:08:24,712 --> 00:08:26,380
You were always pissed off.

91
00:08:26,464 --> 00:08:30,551
Of course, back then,
you were just a boy who lost his eyesight.

92
00:08:31,552 --> 00:08:35,097
And now,
you're the Devil of Hell's Kitchen.

93
00:08:36,474 --> 00:08:37,642
You've heard of me.

94
00:08:37,725 --> 00:08:39,936
I live in an orphanage, not under a rock.

95
00:08:41,312 --> 00:08:45,566
I just never imagined it'd be one of ours
running around in that Halloween costume.

96
00:08:46,484 --> 00:08:48,694
The things I've heard you can do...

97
00:08:49,529 --> 00:08:51,072
You are blind, right?

98
00:08:51,906 --> 00:08:53,991
You weren't just faking it the whole time?

99
00:08:55,826 --> 00:08:57,078
Congratulations.

100
00:08:57,954 --> 00:08:59,497
You finally caught me.

101
00:09:00,122 --> 00:09:01,749
It's not a fair question?

102
00:09:04,168 --> 00:09:06,170
Yeah, the accident blinded me.

103
00:09:07,463 --> 00:09:11,342
It just also, uh,
sharpened my other senses.

104
00:09:12,718 --> 00:09:14,178
Not to worry, Sister.

105
00:09:15,513 --> 00:09:16,764
Those days are behind me.

106
00:09:17,640 --> 00:09:21,686
I'm deaf in my right ear,
and I can't even walk to the bathroom now.

107
00:09:21,769 --> 00:09:24,522
Yeah, well, you're pretty banged up.

108
00:09:25,439 --> 00:09:27,733
Your spine, your hip.

109
00:09:30,152 --> 00:09:33,364
Well, the days of doing backflips
might be over, but...

110
00:09:33,906 --> 00:09:35,992
you'll get back on your feet.

111
00:09:37,535 --> 00:09:39,078
Now that you're out of the woods...

112
00:09:40,830 --> 00:09:41,914
You want me to go.

113
00:09:44,208 --> 00:09:45,501
It's not a convalescent home.

114
00:09:45,585 --> 00:09:47,503
-I understand.
-I'm sorry.

115
00:09:47,587 --> 00:09:48,754
I'll figure something out.

116
00:09:51,215 --> 00:09:54,302
There must be at least one person
I can call for you.

117
00:09:56,095 --> 00:09:56,929
No.

118
00:09:59,807 --> 00:10:01,017
There's no one.

119
00:10:02,685 --> 00:10:05,021
Yeah. No, I filed that story already.

120
00:10:05,104 --> 00:10:06,480
Yeah! No, look...

121
00:10:06,564 --> 00:10:08,941
Oh, that. No.
Uh, part five still needs a quote.

122
00:10:09,025 --> 00:10:11,110
I put out a few lines.
We'll get a bite soon.

123
00:10:11,193 --> 00:10:12,278
Yeah, okay. [chuckles]

124
00:10:12,361 --> 00:10:14,488
Yeah, I'll have it for you
by the end of the day.

125
00:10:14,572 --> 00:10:16,365
All right. Yeah. Bye.

126
00:11:04,997 --> 00:11:07,249
[sighs] Shit.

127
00:11:07,333 --> 00:11:09,043
[Karen] <i>What am I doing here, Matt?</i>

128
00:11:09,126 --> 00:11:12,296
I have something that I need you to see.

129
00:11:18,094 --> 00:11:19,470
I'm Daredevil.

130
00:11:32,608 --> 00:11:33,609
[Matt] <i>How was the walk?</i>

131
00:11:33,693 --> 00:11:36,112
I just needed some space.

132
00:11:36,195 --> 00:11:37,822
-It's a lot...
-No, of course. I get it.

133
00:11:38,781 --> 00:11:40,449
-Please, come in.
-Thank you.

134
00:11:46,288 --> 00:11:47,790
Can you see me?

135
00:11:48,624 --> 00:11:51,836
No. No, not "see" exactly.

136
00:11:53,254 --> 00:11:54,797
It's different. It's, um...

137
00:11:57,299 --> 00:11:58,342
I think it's better.

138
00:11:58,426 --> 00:12:00,678
"Different" how? "Better" how?

139
00:12:02,346 --> 00:12:05,683
Well, I can sense things about you.

140
00:12:06,642 --> 00:12:07,810
Okay. Like what?

141
00:12:08,728 --> 00:12:11,689
[sighing] Oh, God.
It's really hard to explain. Um...

142
00:12:12,231 --> 00:12:13,566
Try me.

143
00:12:13,649 --> 00:12:16,360
I know that you stopped
on the way over here.

144
00:12:16,444 --> 00:12:18,154
At our favorite Indian place.

145
00:12:20,197 --> 00:12:23,075
Probably it was a trip down memory lane,

146
00:12:23,159 --> 00:12:25,953
'cause you didn't eat
but you did order a drink.

147
00:12:26,620 --> 00:12:29,123
See, I can smell the curry
on your clothes, and I can...

148
00:12:29,790 --> 00:12:31,709
taste the Jameson's off your lips.

149
00:12:31,792 --> 00:12:34,587
I know that just telling you all that
makes you uncomfortable...

150
00:12:36,088 --> 00:12:38,048
'cause I can hear your heartbeat.

151
00:12:41,051 --> 00:12:42,344
This is humiliating.

152
00:12:42,428 --> 00:12:46,223
Karen, I should've told you.
You have every right to be angry--

153
00:12:46,307 --> 00:12:49,059
Yeah. I should be.
I should be really angry at you.

154
00:12:49,935 --> 00:12:51,771
But I watched you fight for me.

155
00:12:52,730 --> 00:12:54,106
Twice, actually.

156
00:12:56,734 --> 00:12:58,277
You know I dreamed about that?

157
00:12:59,195 --> 00:13:02,406
I played it over in my mind
again and again, and I keep...

158
00:13:03,073 --> 00:13:05,159
How can I be this mad
at someone who saved my life?

159
00:13:05,242 --> 00:13:09,371
Because he's your friend and you care
for him and he broke your trust.

160
00:13:09,455 --> 00:13:11,874
Yeah, well, stop agreeing with me.
It's making it worse.

161
00:13:12,583 --> 00:13:13,501
[Matt chuckles]

162
00:13:16,545 --> 00:13:17,963
Can I get you a drink?

163
00:13:22,009 --> 00:13:22,843
[chuckles]

164
00:13:24,637 --> 00:13:26,055
And he knows I nodded.

165
00:13:28,098 --> 00:13:32,686
So, the whole cane thing,
it's just... an act?

166
00:13:33,270 --> 00:13:34,146
Yep.

167
00:13:36,232 --> 00:13:37,233
Sorry. Why?

168
00:13:41,403 --> 00:13:43,322
[stammering] Why didn't you trust me?

169
00:13:43,405 --> 00:13:45,449
-What, did you think I would judge you?
-No.

170
00:13:45,533 --> 00:13:47,201
I didn't judge Frank.
Why would I judge you?

171
00:13:47,284 --> 00:13:49,870
Well, maybe you should judge Frank.

172
00:13:49,954 --> 00:13:51,664
Castle's a killer. I'm not.

173
00:13:51,747 --> 00:13:53,874
You don't always know
what motivates people.

174
00:13:53,958 --> 00:13:58,003
Uh, yeah, but I know when they lie to me.
Their heartbeats tell me.

175
00:14:00,673 --> 00:14:03,342
Here's what I know.
I will never lie to you again.

176
00:14:05,261 --> 00:14:08,013
That's a promise. All right?
Ask me anything.

177
00:14:16,230 --> 00:14:17,481
Where do you keep it?

178
00:14:18,691 --> 00:14:21,443
In the closet. In the chest.

179
00:14:27,074 --> 00:14:28,409
[Karen] Holy shit.

180
00:14:30,202 --> 00:14:32,162
What... what happens now?

181
00:14:32,246 --> 00:14:35,499
It's over. That's it.
I'm gonna leave Daredevil behind.

182
00:14:35,583 --> 00:14:38,085
Really? You can just do that?

183
00:14:39,169 --> 00:14:40,170
Yeah.

184
00:14:42,882 --> 00:14:46,969
You know... you and Foggy
had me almost convinced it was alcohol.

185
00:14:47,052 --> 00:14:48,012
It makes a lot of sense.

186
00:14:48,095 --> 00:14:51,432
You know, the secrecy, abandoning social
and professional commitments.

187
00:14:51,515 --> 00:14:53,809
It... It certainly sounds like an addict.

188
00:14:53,893 --> 00:14:57,813
-[scoffing] Well, it's not like that.
-Help me out, then, because I'm not you.

189
00:14:59,607 --> 00:15:01,817
I can't tell if you're lying to me or not.

190
00:15:20,085 --> 00:15:24,006
I don't need him
to be a part of me anymore.

191
00:15:26,050 --> 00:15:27,676
And I don't want him to be.

192
00:15:31,555 --> 00:15:33,140
I want to believe you.

193
00:15:38,646 --> 00:15:41,065
I'm not so sure Daredevil is the problem.

194
00:15:46,987 --> 00:15:47,821
Ouch.

195
00:15:50,074 --> 00:15:51,075
[knocking at door]

196
00:15:51,158 --> 00:15:52,660
-[door opens]
-Shit.

197
00:15:53,786 --> 00:15:54,703
[Foggy] Karen?

198
00:15:54,787 --> 00:15:56,372
Hey, Karen, you here?

199
00:15:59,500 --> 00:16:01,251
-Hey. You okay?
-Hey. Yeah.

200
00:16:01,335 --> 00:16:05,798
-Yeah, yeah, fine. Thanks for coming.
-Did the building manager let you in?

201
00:16:05,881 --> 00:16:06,840
Um...

202
00:16:07,508 --> 00:16:10,928
I thought you said
you were packing the place up.

203
00:16:11,011 --> 00:16:12,096
Yeah. Uh...

204
00:16:12,972 --> 00:16:14,139
Remember how I told you

205
00:16:14,223 --> 00:16:17,685
I was gonna talk to Matt's landlord
about letting his place go?

206
00:16:17,768 --> 00:16:18,602
Uh-huh.

207
00:16:19,561 --> 00:16:20,646
Surprise. [chuckles]

208
00:16:22,189 --> 00:16:24,733
What, so when you asked me
to help you move boxes...

209
00:16:24,817 --> 00:16:26,568
Uh, yeah, I lied.

210
00:16:26,652 --> 00:16:29,113
I mean, technically it was more of,
like, a ruse.

211
00:16:29,196 --> 00:16:30,030
[chuckles]

212
00:16:30,781 --> 00:16:32,616
-Gotcha. You rused.
-Hmm.

213
00:16:32,700 --> 00:16:34,785
Journalism has changed you, Page.

214
00:16:35,786 --> 00:16:36,912
So what am I doing here?

215
00:16:36,996 --> 00:16:38,998
Oh! Uh... Right. Yeah. So... Wait! Are you living here?

216
00:16:42,835 --> 00:16:45,713
Oh! No. God, no.
I'm just paying the bills,

217
00:16:45,796 --> 00:16:48,132
or some of them,
until Matt gets back, but, um...

218
00:16:51,885 --> 00:16:53,137
Matt's being evicted.

219
00:16:53,220 --> 00:16:56,640
Yeah, I need you to help me convince
his landlord to give me an extension.

220
00:16:57,474 --> 00:16:59,560
-[sighs] Karen--
-No, just, carrying two rents...

221
00:16:59,643 --> 00:17:02,021
-I'm behind this month. That's all.
-[sighs deeply]

222
00:17:15,325 --> 00:17:18,078
As much as it hurts me to say this,

223
00:17:19,329 --> 00:17:20,706
you're a reporter.

224
00:17:20,789 --> 00:17:24,460
Look at the facts.
A building fell on Matt. A big one.

225
00:17:24,543 --> 00:17:26,295
And nobody's heard from him since.

226
00:17:26,879 --> 00:17:28,338
Matt's dead.

227
00:17:30,799 --> 00:17:33,469
That's the first time
I've said that out loud.

228
00:17:36,221 --> 00:17:37,639
I don't want to accept it, either.

229
00:17:38,432 --> 00:17:40,559
Especially since I'm the one who...

230
00:17:40,642 --> 00:17:42,186
-you know...
-No.

231
00:17:42,269 --> 00:17:44,313
-...brought him the Devil suit.
-Hey, don't...

232
00:17:45,731 --> 00:17:47,149
do that to yourself.

233
00:17:48,150 --> 00:17:50,569
You know that was his choice.
He'd have gotten to that suit

234
00:17:50,652 --> 00:17:52,488
whether you brought it to him or not.

235
00:17:53,530 --> 00:17:54,531
I know.

236
00:17:57,076 --> 00:18:00,704
But it doesn't stop me from wishing
I'd brought him some sweatpants instead.

237
00:18:05,793 --> 00:18:09,713
You're right. Everything you're saying
is making sense. I just...

238
00:18:12,257 --> 00:18:13,759
I know it's irrational...

239
00:18:15,511 --> 00:18:16,887
but I can just feel it.

240
00:18:19,765 --> 00:18:20,808
He's not dead.

241
00:18:28,816 --> 00:18:32,111
I'll take care of these
and one more month's rent.

242
00:18:32,194 --> 00:18:33,362
No, no. Uh...

243
00:18:33,445 --> 00:18:35,781
Let's just split 'em down the middle,
50-50.

244
00:18:36,824 --> 00:18:40,702
Fine, but then that's it, okay?

245
00:18:46,542 --> 00:18:47,584
[Maggie] Come on, then.

246
00:18:47,668 --> 00:18:50,921
[Lantom] It's away from the kids,
so you can stay here as long as you need.

247
00:18:51,588 --> 00:18:52,965
Bit musty, though.

248
00:18:53,632 --> 00:18:55,509
[Matt] I can't smell anything anyway.

249
00:18:56,009 --> 00:18:58,011
[melodic chanting in distance]

250
00:19:10,065 --> 00:19:12,776
-That music...
-[Lantom] The chapel is right above us.

251
00:19:14,027 --> 00:19:16,196
Yeah, but isn't that Arabic?

252
00:19:17,239 --> 00:19:19,741
The mosque on 39th had a pipe burst,

253
00:19:19,825 --> 00:19:22,786
so we're sharing our space
for a few weeks.

254
00:19:23,704 --> 00:19:25,914
Hell's Kitchen takes care of its own.

255
00:19:28,208 --> 00:19:29,751
[Maggie] This will have to do.

256
00:19:30,836 --> 00:19:34,590
It's also the laundry room,
so it'll be noisy at times.

257
00:19:36,175 --> 00:19:38,302
[Matt] I can always turn a deaf ear to it.

258
00:19:38,385 --> 00:19:41,263
[Maggie] See?
There's a bright side to everything.

259
00:19:42,556 --> 00:19:44,391
-I'll need help getting him into bed.
-Yeah.

260
00:19:44,474 --> 00:19:46,393
No, I'd like to stay up a while. Then I can take it from here, Paul.

261
00:19:50,480 --> 00:19:52,274
Matthew, if you wanna talk--

262
00:19:52,357 --> 00:19:53,692
No. Thank you.

263
00:19:59,406 --> 00:20:00,407
So...

264
00:20:02,326 --> 00:20:04,036
the bed's right in front of you.

265
00:20:05,662 --> 00:20:07,664
Sister Anne wired you up.

266
00:20:10,334 --> 00:20:14,671
If you press that,
we'll hear you upstairs and come running.

267
00:20:15,839 --> 00:20:18,133
Because we don't have
anything better to do.

268
00:20:19,218 --> 00:20:20,969
Very Christian of you.

269
00:20:22,596 --> 00:20:27,726
Angry, sarcastic... and stubborn.

270
00:20:29,311 --> 00:20:31,271
Maybe you don't have any friends.

271
00:20:32,439 --> 00:20:35,943
Someone once told me
that warriors were meant to be alone.

272
00:20:38,028 --> 00:20:40,113
That caring for people would make me weak.

273
00:20:40,989 --> 00:20:42,824
Sounds like he needed to get laid.

274
00:20:42,908 --> 00:20:45,118
Ha! That actually explains a lot.

275
00:20:45,869 --> 00:20:47,329
I mean, he was right, of course.

276
00:20:49,331 --> 00:20:51,083
I let people in, I paid a price.

277
00:20:51,750 --> 00:20:53,794
I won't make that mistake again.

278
00:20:53,877 --> 00:20:54,878
What is this?

279
00:20:55,671 --> 00:20:57,297
[Maggie] Dug those out of storage.

280
00:20:58,715 --> 00:21:01,009
You were probably
the last one to read 'em.

281
00:21:09,518 --> 00:21:10,727
[Matt] My Bible.

282
00:21:10,811 --> 00:21:13,063
All right. I get the hint.

283
00:21:14,982 --> 00:21:18,568
And I get the sense things are complicated
with you and the guy upstairs.

284
00:21:18,652 --> 00:21:20,988
[chuckles] No. Not at all.

285
00:21:21,530 --> 00:21:24,700
If anything, I'd say we finally know
where we stand with each other.

286
00:21:27,202 --> 00:21:29,246
"There was a man from the land of Uz..."

287
00:21:29,329 --> 00:21:30,330
Book of Job.

288
00:21:30,414 --> 00:21:31,790
The Book of Job.

289
00:21:31,873 --> 00:21:33,667
The story of God's perfect servant, Job.

290
00:21:33,750 --> 00:21:35,919
He prayed every day at dawn,

291
00:21:36,003 --> 00:21:38,714
with his knees on the ground,
his face in the dirt.

292
00:21:38,797 --> 00:21:41,800
Slaughtered ten goats,
one for each of his children,

293
00:21:41,883 --> 00:21:43,969
and burned them
at the altar in God's honor.

294
00:21:44,052 --> 00:21:46,722
Of all of God's soldiers, Job,
he was the most loyal.

295
00:21:46,805 --> 00:21:48,181
I know the story, Matthew.

296
00:21:48,265 --> 00:21:49,975
Oh. Then you know what happens next.

297
00:21:51,351 --> 00:21:53,979
God murdered all ten of his children
in cold blood.

298
00:21:54,563 --> 00:21:56,189
Scorched every inch of Job's land.

299
00:21:56,273 --> 00:21:59,192
Lashed at his body till his skin
was covered in bloody welts.

300
00:21:59,276 --> 00:22:02,654
God rained shit and misery
on the life of his most perfect servant.

301
00:22:02,738 --> 00:22:05,866
And still... Job would not curse him.

302
00:22:08,368 --> 00:22:09,703
You know what I realized?

303
00:22:11,246 --> 00:22:12,539
Job was a pussy.

304
00:22:16,001 --> 00:22:18,003
You see, that was me, Sister.

305
00:22:19,963 --> 00:22:21,298
I suffered willingly. I gave my, uh...

306
00:22:25,344 --> 00:22:29,264
sweat and blood and skin
without complaint.

307
00:22:29,348 --> 00:22:32,434
Because I too believed
I was God's soldier. [chuckles]

308
00:22:35,979 --> 00:22:37,439
Well, not anymore.

309
00:22:40,859 --> 00:22:42,819
I am what I do in the dark now.

310
00:22:45,322 --> 00:22:46,948
I bleed only for myself.

311
00:23:11,723 --> 00:23:12,724
[scoffs]

312
00:23:19,481 --> 00:23:20,857
You weren't listening.

313
00:23:23,652 --> 00:23:25,570
I heard every spiteful word.

314
00:23:27,072 --> 00:23:29,950
You might hate God right now,
but the feeling is not mutual.

315
00:23:30,033 --> 00:23:31,701
No, I don't hate him.

316
00:23:33,370 --> 00:23:35,372
I've just seen his true face, is all.

317
00:23:36,998 --> 00:23:39,876
And, for the record, I had friends.
I had a life.

318
00:23:40,794 --> 00:23:42,796
I care about people,

319
00:23:42,879 --> 00:23:46,007
and I'm choosing to let them
believe that I'm gone because I am.

320
00:23:48,635 --> 00:23:49,761
I'm not Job.

321
00:23:49,845 --> 00:23:50,679
[sniffles]

322
00:23:52,389 --> 00:23:53,890
And I know my truth now.

323
00:23:54,850 --> 00:23:55,851
What truth?

324
00:24:01,857 --> 00:24:05,444
Well, that in front of this God...

325
00:24:07,404 --> 00:24:10,532
I'd rather die as the Devil
than live as Matt Murdock.

326
00:24:12,033 --> 00:24:13,743
[piano music playing]

327
00:24:53,074 --> 00:24:57,120
-[inmates chattering indistinctly]
-[piano music continues over speakers]

328
00:25:14,054 --> 00:25:15,305
Quiet!

329
00:25:15,388 --> 00:25:16,556
[chattering stops]

330
00:25:26,024 --> 00:25:28,193
[door buzzes and opens]

331
00:25:40,413 --> 00:25:42,457
We have good news, Mr. Fisk.

332
00:25:42,541 --> 00:25:45,293
Your appeal is proceeding as discussed.

333
00:25:47,420 --> 00:25:48,463
News.

334
00:25:50,090 --> 00:25:52,008
That implies new information.

335
00:25:53,301 --> 00:25:54,719
Let's start there.

336
00:25:55,470 --> 00:25:58,598
[Donovan] We'll remind you,
we're only the messengers.

337
00:25:58,682 --> 00:26:01,059
We've been doing everything we can
to help her.

338
00:26:01,142 --> 00:26:05,438
[Lee] But there have been some setbacks
regarding Ms. Marianna's return.

339
00:26:05,522 --> 00:26:08,358
[Donovan] It's going to be
more complicated than we anticipated.

340
00:26:15,407 --> 00:26:16,533
How so?

341
00:26:17,492 --> 00:26:20,662
[Donovan] The federal government has
decided to charge her as an accessory.

342
00:26:21,204 --> 00:26:25,083
If they locate her overseas
or she sets foot on US soil,

343
00:26:25,166 --> 00:26:27,669
she'll face prosecution and prison.

344
00:26:37,220 --> 00:26:38,388
I see.

345
00:26:41,516 --> 00:26:42,601
Leave.

346
00:26:43,935 --> 00:26:45,437
[door buzzes and opens]

347
00:26:45,937 --> 00:26:47,230
[footsteps receding]

348
00:26:47,772 --> 00:26:48,607
[door closes]

349
00:27:18,511 --> 00:27:19,512
[snapping] [muffled snapping]

350
00:27:55,840 --> 00:27:56,675
[grunts]

351
00:27:58,301 --> 00:27:59,135
[groaning]

352
00:28:00,845 --> 00:28:01,680
[exhales]

353
00:28:03,098 --> 00:28:04,099
[panting] [grunts]

354
00:28:13,358 --> 00:28:15,026
[Maggie] What on earth are you doing?

355
00:28:16,820 --> 00:28:18,154
Falling.

356
00:28:21,700 --> 00:28:23,326
I brought you something.

357
00:28:23,410 --> 00:28:25,745
Is it food? I can't smell anything.

358
00:28:25,829 --> 00:28:27,372
A hot toddy.

359
00:28:27,455 --> 00:28:29,207
It'll help open your sinuses.

360
00:28:32,460 --> 00:28:33,503
Thank you.

361
00:28:33,586 --> 00:28:35,672
And you need to keep taking these.

362
00:28:47,684 --> 00:28:52,731
Well, it's hot, but... I still can't taste
anything but blood and ash.

363
00:28:55,817 --> 00:28:57,026
Cheers.

364
00:28:57,110 --> 00:29:00,447
Pills and liquor,
modern medicine at its finest.

365
00:29:00,530 --> 00:29:01,823
Easy, smart-ass.

366
00:29:01,906 --> 00:29:04,367
If you want modern medicine,
the door's straight ahead.

367
00:29:05,410 --> 00:29:08,037
-It doesn't matter anyway.
-That's the spirit.

368
00:29:09,622 --> 00:29:11,166
How's the buzzing?

369
00:29:11,249 --> 00:29:12,375
Not getting better.

370
00:29:13,209 --> 00:29:14,878
Give it time.

371
00:29:14,961 --> 00:29:17,088
After the beating you took,
everything's swollen.

372
00:29:19,090 --> 00:29:21,342
Maybe your hearing will come back
when it goes down.

373
00:29:23,178 --> 00:29:26,347
Or maybe it'll come back when you take
your head out of your ass.

374
00:29:26,431 --> 00:29:27,849
[scoffing laughter]

375
00:29:28,933 --> 00:29:30,560
How many of these did you have?

376
00:29:32,687 --> 00:29:34,022
What you said...

377
00:29:36,149 --> 00:29:39,444
about rather dying as the Devil
than living as Matt Murdock...

378
00:29:42,697 --> 00:29:46,618
I just want you to know
that I think you're a hero.

379
00:29:46,701 --> 00:29:49,329
Hiding down here,
feeling sorry for yourself.

380
00:29:50,163 --> 00:29:51,831
I mean, just out back,

381
00:29:51,915 --> 00:29:55,460
there's an orphanage full of kids
who've lost everything and everyone.

382
00:29:56,419 --> 00:30:00,548
Some of them are disabled,
much worse off than you ever were.

383
00:30:00,632 --> 00:30:03,676
And they're still trying to make
the most out of life, the little cowards.

384
00:30:03,760 --> 00:30:05,220
Okay. All right.

385
00:30:06,304 --> 00:30:10,517
And here you are,
with all the gifts God gave you.

386
00:30:10,600 --> 00:30:16,064
Handsome, smart, a law degree,
and people who care about you.

387
00:30:16,147 --> 00:30:18,608
And you're bravely giving up.

388
00:30:18,691 --> 00:30:20,485
[Matt] Well, you know, thank you...

389
00:30:21,027 --> 00:30:22,654
for the tough love, Sister.

390
00:30:23,571 --> 00:30:27,617
And your charmingly simplistic
view of God and the world.

391
00:30:29,160 --> 00:30:31,246
I appreciate everything
you've done for me, I do,

392
00:30:31,329 --> 00:30:34,499
but don't for a second think you know
anything about me or my life.

393
00:30:34,582 --> 00:30:36,751
I've been a nun for 30 years.

394
00:30:37,418 --> 00:30:39,337
I know self-pity when I hear it.

395
00:30:39,921 --> 00:30:41,005
Okay, good.

396
00:30:42,382 --> 00:30:44,717
Your father was famous around here.

397
00:30:45,718 --> 00:30:47,262
I saw him fight.

398
00:30:50,974 --> 00:30:52,934
I saw him go down many times.

399
00:30:54,143 --> 00:30:55,770
But he never stayed down.

400
00:31:04,988 --> 00:31:05,989
[sighs]

401
00:31:14,205 --> 00:31:16,124
[siren wailing in distance]

402
00:32:07,383 --> 00:32:08,217
Oh. [exhales]

403
00:32:17,518 --> 00:32:18,353
[panting]

404
00:32:24,192 --> 00:32:25,193
[rumbling]

405
00:32:33,493 --> 00:32:34,911
[rumbling starts and stops]

406
00:32:36,037 --> 00:32:39,165
[rumbling starts and stops]

407
00:32:46,798 --> 00:32:49,008
[train rumbling in distance]

408
00:32:56,808 --> 00:32:59,310
[train rumbling in distance]

409
00:34:03,374 --> 00:34:04,751
[grunting and panting]

410
00:34:07,545 --> 00:34:08,379
[groans]

411
00:34:23,102 --> 00:34:24,645
What in God's name have...

412
00:34:25,229 --> 00:34:26,564
-Feel that?
-Feel what?

413
00:34:26,647 --> 00:34:28,232
Three subway lines run beneath us.

414
00:34:30,651 --> 00:34:33,488
At any given time, there are
six different trains vibrating the ground.

415
00:34:34,405 --> 00:34:35,656
That was the E train.

416
00:34:35,740 --> 00:34:36,824
Was it now?

417
00:34:36,908 --> 00:34:38,242
You brought food.

418
00:34:38,326 --> 00:34:39,702
I did. I brought you some...

419
00:34:40,661 --> 00:34:43,247
Beef ravioli from Nonna's. Nice.

420
00:34:44,332 --> 00:34:45,792
Now you're just showing off.

421
00:34:50,129 --> 00:34:52,340
[Maggie] He wants to know
that he's still got it.

422
00:34:52,423 --> 00:34:54,592
[Lantom] I am not comfortable
with that idea.

423
00:34:54,675 --> 00:34:56,594
Now you're uncomfortable?

424
00:34:58,137 --> 00:35:00,640
Heal the body, and the spirit will follow.

425
00:35:00,723 --> 00:35:02,517
It's the other way around.

426
00:35:03,684 --> 00:35:04,977
[Maggie] He needs this.

427
00:35:06,020 --> 00:35:08,189
It's the only damn thing
that's gotten him out of bed.

428
00:35:08,272 --> 00:35:09,774
So please just do it.

429
00:35:21,452 --> 00:35:23,037
Thanks for making this happen.

430
00:35:23,121 --> 00:35:24,997
Hands should be used for God's work.

431
00:35:26,040 --> 00:35:30,211
-Yeah? That's why he made me this way?
-No. That's why he made boxing.

432
00:35:30,294 --> 00:35:31,129
[door opens]

433
00:35:32,713 --> 00:35:34,507
-[Matt] Gloves?
-[Maggie] Helmet first.

434
00:35:34,590 --> 00:35:36,175
No, I can't. It'll throw me off.

435
00:35:36,259 --> 00:35:38,719
-Don't be an idiot.
-Sister, listen to me.

436
00:35:38,803 --> 00:35:42,181
For this to work,
I have to feel and hear everything.

437
00:35:42,265 --> 00:35:44,600
[Lantom] Now, remember the deal.
Keep your mouth shut.

438
00:35:45,184 --> 00:35:46,561
[Edmund] Beats the Hail Marys.

439
00:35:52,108 --> 00:35:53,943
You want me to hit a blind guy?

440
00:35:55,528 --> 00:35:56,529
All right.

441
00:36:00,741 --> 00:36:01,951
[grunts]

442
00:36:05,705 --> 00:36:06,747
[grunting]

443
00:36:23,514 --> 00:36:25,308
[Lantom] Cut! Time!

444
00:36:27,810 --> 00:36:29,437
-You good?
-Yeah, I'm good.

445
00:36:30,605 --> 00:36:32,356
Damn. He hits hard.

446
00:36:33,941 --> 00:36:37,278
It's really something.
To see it with my own eyes.

447
00:36:37,361 --> 00:36:40,489
No. Something feels off.
It feels like I'm underwater.

448
00:36:40,573 --> 00:36:42,325
-Maybe we should stop.
-No, no, no.

449
00:36:42,408 --> 00:36:43,701
Ding-ding. Let's go again.

450
00:36:55,296 --> 00:36:56,297
[muffled buzzing] [Lantom] Matthew?

451
00:37:22,740 --> 00:37:23,741
Matthew!

452
00:37:45,930 --> 00:37:47,640
[Maggie] You should see the other guy.

453
00:37:53,437 --> 00:37:55,106
For what it's worth...

454
00:37:58,317 --> 00:37:59,610
you were incredible.

455
00:38:01,946 --> 00:38:02,947
Thank you. Sister, I...

456
00:38:06,367 --> 00:38:09,120
Did your head spin around?
Then wear it for me.

457
00:38:14,709 --> 00:38:16,502
You've been very kind to me.

458
00:38:17,837 --> 00:38:19,797
-I have, haven't I?
-[sniffles]

459
00:38:19,880 --> 00:38:22,758
-And patient. Very, very patient.
-[chuckles]

460
00:38:23,759 --> 00:38:25,886
Don't tell anyone.
They'll think I've gone soft.

461
00:38:25,970 --> 00:38:28,264
No. I don't think
there's any danger of that.

462
00:38:30,224 --> 00:38:31,392
Let me look at you.

463
00:38:35,187 --> 00:38:36,981
I used to sew up my dad.

464
00:38:38,149 --> 00:38:40,651
And your stitches are perfect.

465
00:38:40,735 --> 00:38:43,404
Well, there's plenty of practice
around here.

466
00:38:47,992 --> 00:38:49,160
Everything okay?

467
00:38:50,119 --> 00:38:51,787
Yeah. It's fine.

468
00:38:53,581 --> 00:38:55,541
I just have to get back upstairs.

469
00:39:03,966 --> 00:39:06,469
I don't suppose there's any hope
you'd come to Mass with me?

470
00:39:10,056 --> 00:39:11,474
Maybe next time.

471
00:39:11,557 --> 00:39:12,892
I'll hold you to that.

472
00:39:15,269 --> 00:39:17,271
[church choir singing]

473
00:40:08,781 --> 00:40:12,576
[woman] Hey! Hey, get off of him!
Hey! What are you doing? Dad!

474
00:40:13,160 --> 00:40:14,829
-Dad! Hey!
-[grunting]

475
00:40:26,340 --> 00:40:27,174
[groaning]

476
00:40:35,641 --> 00:40:38,853
Help! Get off! Help!

477
00:40:39,937 --> 00:40:41,647
Oh, my God! Dad! Dad...

478
00:40:42,398 --> 00:40:43,399
[grunting] [glass shatters]

479
00:40:51,157 --> 00:40:53,159
[woman] Stay with me.
We'll get you to the hospital.

480
00:41:12,386 --> 00:41:13,596
Come on!

481
00:41:15,347 --> 00:41:17,975
[man] Hey, asshole,
this was none of your business.

482
00:41:19,435 --> 00:41:20,436
Come on.

483
00:41:42,249 --> 00:41:43,667
[panting]

484
00:41:48,088 --> 00:41:49,924
[man 1] We should
kill this son of a bitch.

485
00:41:50,007 --> 00:41:51,759
[man 2] Nah, man. Leave him.

486
00:41:55,971 --> 00:41:56,972
[Matt] Hold on.

487
00:42:09,443 --> 00:42:10,569
God forgive me.

488
00:42:11,737 --> 00:42:12,738
[police siren wailing]

489
00:42:14,949 --> 00:42:16,867
Leave him. Let's get out of here.

490
00:42:49,066 --> 00:42:52,570
We seriously out of turkey?
You didn't swing by the deli?

491
00:42:53,279 --> 00:42:55,030
I did, actually.

492
00:42:55,114 --> 00:42:59,034
I ran into a little payment snafu
at the register.

493
00:43:00,244 --> 00:43:03,497
I wanted to make it through the party
before I brought it up.

494
00:43:04,206 --> 00:43:05,040
Huh.

495
00:43:05,541 --> 00:43:08,502
Uh, which card did you use?
The red Visa, right?

496
00:43:08,586 --> 00:43:10,421
-Yeah, of course. Yeah.
-Huh.

497
00:43:11,755 --> 00:43:13,048
Hey, Dad.

498
00:43:13,132 --> 00:43:15,467
Hey! There's the birthday goon!

499
00:43:15,551 --> 00:43:18,762
<i>Masi</i> Savina wanted to know
if you're ruining dinner.

500
00:43:18,846 --> 00:43:19,680
[chuckles]

501
00:43:20,556 --> 00:43:22,308
Excuse me?

502
00:43:22,975 --> 00:43:26,061
Is she trying to undermine
my culinary talents again?

503
00:43:26,145 --> 00:43:27,146
Get over here.

504
00:43:28,147 --> 00:43:31,191
Let me show you
how a master chef does his thing.

505
00:43:32,401 --> 00:43:33,944
Check this out.

506
00:43:35,487 --> 00:43:37,281
See what I'm doing here, Sami?

507
00:43:37,364 --> 00:43:39,617
This is a technique called "skimming."

508
00:43:40,534 --> 00:43:42,411
High degree of difficulty.

509
00:43:43,037 --> 00:43:43,871
Ta-da!

510
00:43:44,538 --> 00:43:46,290
-Wanna do the honors?
-Yes.

511
00:43:49,043 --> 00:43:52,296
[in Hindi] Are you positive
you used the red Visa?

512
00:43:52,379 --> 00:43:56,383
I paid that one last week.
That one should be good.

513
00:43:56,467 --> 00:44:00,554
I tried the red Visa, the blue Visa,
the silver Mastercard...

514
00:44:00,638 --> 00:44:03,766
I even tried my library card.

515
00:44:05,893 --> 00:44:06,727
[chuckles]

516
00:44:07,853 --> 00:44:08,979
It's okay.

517
00:44:09,647 --> 00:44:11,982
-Nothing we haven't handled before.
-Hmm.

518
00:44:13,025 --> 00:44:15,069
[in English] <i>If I could have the floor</i>
<i>for a minute?</i>

519
00:44:15,152 --> 00:44:16,987
If you haven't heard by now,

520
00:44:17,071 --> 00:44:19,823
despite Nihar shouting it
from the rooftops...

521
00:44:19,907 --> 00:44:21,075
[chuckling]

522
00:44:21,158 --> 00:44:25,663
...my courageous sister-in-law
is now 100% cancer-free.

523
00:44:26,246 --> 00:44:27,081
[cheering]

524
00:44:28,749 --> 00:44:31,168
We know that it hasn't been easy for you,

525
00:44:31,710 --> 00:44:33,545
with all the obstacles you've faced.

526
00:44:34,588 --> 00:44:37,633
Being denied insurance
over and over again.

527
00:44:38,550 --> 00:44:41,095
Those asshole institutions
running you over like a tank.

528
00:44:41,178 --> 00:44:42,179
[Seema clears throat]

529
00:44:45,808 --> 00:44:47,017
Anyway... [chuckles]

530
00:44:47,726 --> 00:44:49,186
tonight, we celebrate.

531
00:44:50,479 --> 00:44:53,899
This one's for you, Saanvi.
Cheers. Cheers.

532
00:44:53,982 --> 00:44:55,901
We couldn't have done it without you,
brother.

533
00:44:55,984 --> 00:44:58,028
No, please don't. [chuckles]

534
00:44:58,112 --> 00:44:59,363
I'm serious, Ray.

535
00:45:01,490 --> 00:45:05,327
You two did the work.
I just wrote a few checks.

536
00:45:08,122 --> 00:45:10,374
What are you doing out here, bug?

537
00:45:10,457 --> 00:45:12,751
Everyone's eaten.
We're waiting to light the candles.

538
00:45:12,835 --> 00:45:13,961
I don't think I want any.

539
00:45:14,878 --> 00:45:18,132
No cake? He doesn't want any cake.

540
00:45:18,215 --> 00:45:20,300
There must be something
seriously wrong with him.

541
00:45:21,719 --> 00:45:23,887
No, seriously, bug. What's up?

542
00:45:23,971 --> 00:45:26,265
I don't know why we had to have
our family party today.

543
00:45:26,348 --> 00:45:29,518
I told you,
Ricky Thomas is having friends over. I could be at his house,
glow bowling in his basement right now.

544
00:45:33,355 --> 00:45:35,816
The Thomases have a bowling alley
in their basement?

545
00:45:36,900 --> 00:45:38,068
Let me tell you something.

546
00:45:38,152 --> 00:45:42,114
Come the summer, you're the one
who's gonna be throwing mad parties,

547
00:45:42,197 --> 00:45:45,159
because the pool
is definitely happening this year.

548
00:45:45,242 --> 00:45:46,869
-Really?
-You bet.

549
00:45:46,952 --> 00:45:49,997
I'm gonna be tossing your butt
off the diving board by June.

550
00:45:50,080 --> 00:45:53,751
Now, what do you say we go inside,
throw back some cake?

551
00:45:53,834 --> 00:45:54,835
-Okay.
-Yeah?

552
00:46:00,048 --> 00:46:02,259
-The pool, huh?
-No, don't.

553
00:46:02,342 --> 00:46:06,180
Listen, Nadia said
one of her literacy tutors quit last week.

554
00:46:06,263 --> 00:46:08,724
Maybe I could pick up some evening hours
at the center--

555
00:46:08,807 --> 00:46:10,934
Not another job.
We've been down this road before.

556
00:46:11,018 --> 00:46:13,854
I know, Ray,
but I can't see another way out.

557
00:46:13,937 --> 00:46:15,439
I'll fix this.

558
00:46:17,357 --> 00:46:18,567
I'll fix everything.

559
00:47:13,831 --> 00:47:16,917
I've got a nine o'clock with Salazar,
so unless you got something quick...

560
00:47:17,000 --> 00:47:20,712
-Salazar just got called downtown.
-Well, make yourself at home.

561
00:47:21,505 --> 00:47:22,506
Thanks.

562
00:47:25,717 --> 00:47:26,844
<i>My performance review.</i>

563
00:47:26,927 --> 00:47:29,096
That's not until
the end of the month, correct?

564
00:47:30,097 --> 00:47:33,767
I'd like it moved up.
I'd like to do it now.

565
00:47:35,018 --> 00:47:36,562
That's a tall order, Ray.

566
00:47:37,354 --> 00:47:39,690
Performance review isn't the kind
of thing we shuffle around.

567
00:47:39,773 --> 00:47:42,568
Then how come mine's
been deferred twice now?

568
00:47:44,695 --> 00:47:46,864
You're denying me
the advancement opportunities

569
00:47:46,947 --> 00:47:48,615
that I have rightfully earned.

570
00:47:48,699 --> 00:47:50,784
No, not the Bureau. You.

571
00:47:51,577 --> 00:47:54,955
Now, why you'd do something like that
to me, I don't have a clue.

572
00:47:55,664 --> 00:47:58,292
But maybe it's time I file a complaint
with the EEO.

573
00:48:00,043 --> 00:48:01,044
You're right.

574
00:48:01,837 --> 00:48:03,171
Your reviews have been deferred

575
00:48:03,255 --> 00:48:06,091
for reasons having nothing to do
with scheduling or restructuring

576
00:48:06,174 --> 00:48:08,802
or whatever bullshit
I fed you at the time.

577
00:48:09,970 --> 00:48:11,763
It's because I'm trying to protect you.

578
00:48:12,431 --> 00:48:13,432
Protect me?

579
00:48:14,349 --> 00:48:16,435
Do you have any idea
what your FICO score is?

580
00:48:18,103 --> 00:48:24,026
-557. Your FICO score is 557.
-So it's not stellar. You know, I--

581
00:48:24,109 --> 00:48:28,113
You're buried in debt,
and that makes you a recruitment target.

582
00:48:28,906 --> 00:48:33,285
It's Bureau policy not to promote someone
with that level of vulnerability.

583
00:48:33,368 --> 00:48:37,164
My circumstances were exceptional,
and you know that.

584
00:48:37,956 --> 00:48:41,209
-My sister-in-law was sick and I--
-I am sorry for that.

585
00:48:41,293 --> 00:48:42,753
Three and a half years.

586
00:48:44,546 --> 00:48:47,716
I haven't had a pay bump
in three and a half years.

587
00:48:48,842 --> 00:48:50,177
I know it's wrong.

588
00:48:51,428 --> 00:48:52,429
I know.

589
00:48:54,514 --> 00:48:56,016
You're a fine agent.

590
00:48:57,017 --> 00:49:01,188
But I can't make this happen for you.
Not until you fix your finances.

591
00:49:05,108 --> 00:49:06,109
But look...

592
00:49:07,194 --> 00:49:08,570
while I got you here... your number's up.

593
00:49:15,243 --> 00:49:17,079
Nice. Nice timing.

594
00:49:17,162 --> 00:49:18,956
It's a shit errand. I get it.

595
00:49:19,039 --> 00:49:23,043
We talk to this guy every month,
and every month he gives us nothing.

596
00:49:24,294 --> 00:49:25,837
It's a nice drive, though.

597
00:49:31,593 --> 00:49:33,887
[door buzzes and opens]

598
00:49:49,861 --> 00:49:54,992
Mr. Fisk, I'm Special Agent Ray Nadeem
with the Federal Bureau of Investigation.

599
00:49:55,951 --> 00:49:59,037
The FBI would like your assistance with...

600
00:50:02,165 --> 00:50:04,751
[sighs] Let's cut to the part
where you tell me to eat shit,

601
00:50:04,835 --> 00:50:06,753
so we can stop
wasting each other's time, huh?

602
00:50:10,590 --> 00:50:13,176
Tell me, Special Agent Nadeem...

603
00:50:15,262 --> 00:50:17,639
do you have anyone in your life
who you love so much,

604
00:50:17,723 --> 00:50:19,725
you'd do anything to protect them?

605
00:50:21,852 --> 00:50:23,228
Are you threatening me?

606
00:50:27,816 --> 00:50:30,610
I have made many mistakes.

607
00:50:34,156 --> 00:50:38,201
But I accept the debt I'm paying
because of them.

608
00:50:39,411 --> 00:50:41,872
But what I will not accept...

609
00:50:43,540 --> 00:50:47,210
is that the woman that I love
should have to pay for them, too.

610
00:50:53,008 --> 00:50:55,427
I would do anything to protect her.

611
00:50:56,720 --> 00:50:58,013
Anything. I'm sorry.

612
00:51:07,481 --> 00:51:09,024
What is it you're saying?

613
00:51:12,903 --> 00:51:14,571
I want to make a deal.

